-- China, India, Indonesia, Malaysia: Asian Local Bonds and Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-11-02T21:42:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-02/china-india-indonesia-malaysia-asian-local-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Japan’s financial markets will be closed for a
public holiday today.  The yen traded at 80.63 per dollar at 8:20 a.m. in Sydney.  China: An October purchasing managers’ index for the non-
manufacturing sector will be released today by the China
Federation of Logistics and Purchasing. The gauge rose to 61.7
in September. A reading above 50 indicates an expansion. The
HSBC China Services PMI will be released today by Markit.  The government will sell 28 billion yuan ($4.2 billion) of
three-year bonds.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 3.13
percent. The yuan was at 6.6787.  India: The central bank plans to sell a combined 60 billion
rupees ($1.35 billion) of 91- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.97
percent. The rupee was at 44.3775 per dollar.  Indonesia: The central bank will keep its benchmark
reference rate unchanged at a record low of 6.5 percent at a
meeting tomorrow, according to the median estimate of 19
economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 11 percent government note due November
2020 was 7.32 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market
Association. The rupiah was at 8,920.  Malaysia: The trade ministry will say today that exports
rose 10.1 percent in September from a year earlier, after a 10.6
percent increase in the previous month, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg News survey. Imports rose 16.3 percent
during the same period, a separate survey shows.  Bank Negara will sell 1.5 billion ringgit ($486 million) of
84-day Islamic notes.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015 was
3.49 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was at
3.083 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Andrea Wong  in Hong Kong at 
